type and vintage; VA guidelines require the appraiser to explain this relationship. Weight paired sales heavily; reconcile near $46/SF."}, "bath": {"range": [6200, 6300], "rationale": "Paired sales bracket $6,200–$6,300. Cost support of $6,000 falls just below — a floor. Reconcile within the paired bracket near $6,250."}}, "step3_adjustments": {"C1": {"gla": {"direction": "negative", "amount_per_unit": -46.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": -6900, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior). At the reconciled rate of $46/SF (drawn from three tightly-clustered current-market pairs), the GLA adjustment is −$6,900. Cost support of $44.40/SF acts as a floor; the market pays slightly above replacement cost for this 2000 vintage."}}, "C2": {"bath": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -6250, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 has 2.5 bathrooms versus the subject''s 2 full (superior). The half-bath increment from two paired sales is approximately $6,250 (midpoint of $6,200–$6,300). Cost support of $6,000 again falls below paired sales — confirming the cost-as-floor pattern across both adjustment types in this VA scenario."}}, "C3": {"gla": {"direction": "positive", "amount_per_unit": 46.0, "units": 120, "computed_amount": 5520, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 3 is 120 SF smaller than the subject (inferior). At the reconciled rate of $46/SF, the GLA adjustment is +$5,520."}}}, "step4_adjusted_prices": {"C1": {"unadjusted": 268000, "adjusted": 261100}, "C2": {"unadjusted": 264500, "adjusted": 258250}, "C3": {"unadjusted": 248000, "adjusted": 253520}}, "step4_reconciliation_narrative": "Adjusted prices cluster in a tight band of approximately $253,520–$261,100 — a spread of roughly $7,500. The three adjusted comparables comfortably bracket and support the $258,000 contract price, and the Certificate of Reasonable Value will support VA financing at the contract price. The VA basic-level scenario introduces two distinctive features beyond conventional mortgage lending. First, the appraiser is assigned by VA — not the lender — ensuring structural independence from the transaction; the appraiser''s obligation runs to the veteran and the VA program, not to the lender''s underwriting needs. Second, the cost-as-floor relationship appears here: both GLA ($44.40/SF) and bathroom ($6,000) cost indications fall below the paired sales range, consistent with a 2000-vintage property in a market paying a modest premium above replacement cost. VA guidelines require this relationship to be explained in the addendum, not just noted. If the CRV had been below the contract price, the veteran would have had specific protections — renegotiation, additional cash to close, or walk-away without penalty — that conventional borrowers do not have.", "tolerance_note": "Student answers are accepted within ±5% of model derived values for paired-sales calculations and within the indicated reconciliation range. Step 3 adjustments accepted within ±13% of the computed amount for GLA and ±12% for the secondary feature."}'::jsonb
