  '{"step1_correct_flags": {"C1": ["gla", "adu"], "C2": ["pool", "loc"], "C3": ["gla", "date"]}, "step1_rationale": "Comp 1 differs in two opposing-direction features: 150 SF larger (superior GLA, negative adjustment) and no ADU (inferior, positive adjustment). Comp 2 differs in two opposing-direction features: no in-ground pool (inferior, positive adjustment) and amenitied/gated location (superior, negative adjustment). Comp 3 differs in two same-direction features: 150 SF smaller (inferior GLA, positive adjustment) and sold 10 months ago (inferior date, positive adjustment). Bathrooms, bedrooms, garage, year built, and condition are equivalent across all three comparables. Each comparable carries exactly two adjustments — five distinct adjustment types are accounted for across the three comparables.", "step2_tables": {"paired": {"gla": {"pair_answers": [44.33, 43.67, 44.0, 63.5], "concluded_range": [43.67, 44.33], "rationale": "Pairs 1–3 cluster very tightly at $43.67–$44.33/SF — exceptionally consistent market support. Pair 4 produces $63.50/SF and must be excluded with documented reasoning. Notably, the Pair 4 result is nearly identical to the GLA cost indication ($65.77/SF), supporting the explanation that Pair 4 reflects cost-influenced pricing rather than typical market behavior."}, "adu": {"pair_answers": [16500, 16000, 16500], "concluded_range": [16000, 16500], "rationale": "Three pairs from confirmed real-property ADU comparables produce $16,000, $16,500, and $16,500 — tight market support. The ADU contribution is roughly 40% of depreciated replacement cost — a structural characteristic, not a data quirk."}, "pool": {"pair_answers": [13500, 13000, 13000], "concluded_range": [13000, 13500], "rationale": "Three pairs produce $13,000, $13,000, and $13,500 — tight market support. New pool replacement cost ($40,000–$50,000) dramatically exceeds market contribution; cost is never appropriate for the pool adjustment."}, "loc": {"pair_answers": [15000, 15500, 16000, 16800], "concluded_range": [15000, 16000], "rationale": "Pairs 1–3 produce $15,000–$16,000 — tight market support. Pair 4 ($16,800) is a modest outlier; address but do not weight heavily. Reconcile within Pairs 1–3."}, "date": {"pair_answers": [0.336, 0.301, 0.331], "concluded_range": [0.29, 0.35], "rationale": "Three resale pairs produce 0.34%, 0.30%, and 0.33%/mo. Tight market support; bracket toward central tendency near 0.325%/mo."}}, "cost": {"gla": {"answer": 65.77, "rationale": "$84.00 × (1 − 0.217) = $65.77/SF. Far exceeds paired sales ($43.67–$44.33/SF) — high ceiling. Note that the Pair 4 outlier ($63.50/SF) is nearly identical to this cost indication, supporting the explanation that Pair 4 reflects cost-influenced rather than market-driven pricing — further reason to exclude it and rely on Pairs 1–3."}, "adu": {"answer": 39520, "rationale": "$49,400 × (1 − 0.20) = $39,520. Roughly 2.4× the paired sales indication ($16,000–$16,500). This large gap is characteristic of ADU valuation: buyers discount secondary units due to financing complexity, management burden, and limited buyer pool. Market evidence governs — cost is a ceiling only."}}}, "step2_reconciliation": {"gla": {"range": [43.5, 44.5], "rationale": "Paired sales support $43.67–$44.33/SF (Pairs 1–3, exceptionally tight). Pair 4 ($63.50/SF) excluded with documented reasoning, supported by its near-alignment with the cost ceiling. Cost support of $65.77/SF acts only as a high ceiling. Reconcile near $44/SF."}, "adu": {"range": [16000, 16500], "rationale": "Three paired sales bracket $16,000–$16,500. Cost support of $39,520 acts only as a ceiling — the gap reflects a structural market characteristic of ADU valuation. Reconcile near $16,250."}, "pool": {"range": [13000, 13500], "rationale": "Three paired sales bracket $13,000–$13,500. No cost method applicable (replacement cost dramatically exceeds market). Reconcile near $13,250."}, "loc": {"range": [15000, 16000], "rationale": "Paired sales support $15,000–$16,000 (Pairs 1–3). Pair 4 ($16,800) addressed but not weighted. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near the midpoint at approximately $15,500."}, "date": {"range": [0.31, 0.34], "rationale": "Paired sales support 0.30–0.34%/mo. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near 0.325%/mo."}}, "step3_adjustments": {"C1": {"gla": {"direction": "negative", "amount_per_unit": -44.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": -6600, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior). At reconciled $44/SF (drawn from Pairs 1–3; Pair 4 outlier excluded with documented reasoning, supported by its near-alignment with the $65.77/SF cost ceiling), the GLA adjustment is −$6,600. Cost support acts only as a high ceiling."}, "adu": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 16250, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 has no ADU while the subject has a 520 SF detached real-property ADU (inferior). The ADU contribution from three paired sales is approximately $16,250 (midpoint of $16,000–$16,500). Cost support of $39,520 acts only as a ceiling — the ~40% market-to-cost ratio is a structural characteristic of ADU valuation, reflecting financing complexity and a narrower buyer pool. Comp 1 has opposing GLA (negative) and ADU (positive) adjustments — both must be applied independently."}}, "C2": {"pool": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 13250, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 has no in-ground pool while the subject has one (inferior). The pool contribution from three paired sales is approximately $13,250 (midpoint of $13,000–$13,500). No cost method applicable — new pool replacement cost dramatically exceeds market contribution."}, "loc": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -15500, "method": "Location Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 is in an amenitied/gated community (superior to the subject''s standard location). The location premium derived from Pairs 1–3 is approximately $15,500 (midpoint of $15,000–$16,000). Pair 4 ($16,800) addressed but not weighted. No cost method applicable. Comp 2 has opposing Pool (positive) and Location (negative) adjustments — both applied independently."}}, "C3": {"gla": {"direction": "positive", "amount_per_unit": 44.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": 6600, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 3 is 150 SF smaller than the subject (inferior). At reconciled $44/SF, the GLA adjustment is +$6,600 — opposing direction from Comp 1''s GLA adjustment, demonstrating that GLA must be applied based on each comp''s relationship to the subject."}, "date": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 14430, "method": "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "rationale": "Comp 3 sold 10 months ago in an appreciating market (inferior date). At reconciled 0.325%/mo: $444,000 × 10 × 0.325 ÷ 100 = $14,430. Three resale pairs support this rate, bringing Comp 3 in line with current market values."}}}, "step4_adjusted_prices": {"C1": {"unadjusted": 462000, "adjusted": 471650}, "C2": {"unadjusted": 461000, "adjusted": 458750}, "C3": {"unadjusted": 444000, "adjusted": 465030}}, "step4_reconciliation_narrative": "Adjusted prices cluster in a band of approximately $458,750–$471,650 — a spread of about $13,000 across three comparables and ten total adjustments. The opinion of market value is well-supported in the $462,000–$470,000 range, comfortably bracketing the $468,000 contract price. This capstone scenario assembles every analytical competency developed across Section 4''s 18 scenarios: paired sales derivation, cost support, outlier identification and exclusion, reconciliation across methods, opposing-direction adjustments, gross adjustment review, and five distinct rationale types — including the ADU, a specialty feature appearing with increasing frequency in residential practice. The central insight about ADU valuation — that the market contribution ($16,000–$16,500) is roughly 40% of the depreciated replacement cost ($39,520) — is not a quirk of this data set; it reflects a structural market characteristic. Buyers face underwriting constraints, management considerations, and a narrower resale market for ADUs. The market prices these factors in, and the appraiser''s job is to extract that market signal from comparable evidence rather than rely on cost. The GLA outlier (Pair 4 at $63.50/SF) provides the secondary insight: its near-identical alignment with the GLA cost indication ($65.77/SF) suggests cost-influenced pricing in that transaction — further evidence that cost and market evidence can diverge substantially for the same property feature. The opposing-direction adjustments on Comps 1 and 2 produce small net figures but meaningful gross figures, and the gross-vs-net distinction is part of the weighting story. Completing this scenario completes all 18 scenarios across Modules 1–6 of Section 4 — Adjustment Analysis.", "tolerance_note": "Student answers are accepted within ±5% of model derived values for paired-sales calculations and within the indicated reconciliation range. Step 3 adjustments accepted within ±13% of the computed amount for GLA, ±12% for fixed-amount features, and ±16% for market conditions."}'::jsonb
FROM scenarios s
JOIN scenario_categories sc ON sc.id = s.category_id
JOIN module_sections ms ON ms.id = sc.section_id
JOIN section_fields f ON f.section_id = ms.id AND f.field_key = 'adjustment_grid'
WHERE sc.code = 'M2-S4-C6'
  AND s.order_index = 3;

COMMIT;

